{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fff15969-592a-43ee-a29c-cf6a46b83078","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Look here for `.ips` crash logs:**\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/     # user apps\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/      # system-wide\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n**To get a core dump** (if you need one for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited        # enable core dumps before running the app\n```\n\nCore files land in `/cores/` by default on macOS.\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash log is often sufficient — it contains the crash thread's backtrace, signal info, and register state. If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames in an `.ips` file, I can help with that too (via the **apple-crash-symbolication** skill).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b99180a1-2a19-41fb-9a8c-61e8b013fddf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app that crashed on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files) in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user apps) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-level). These are Apple crash logs.\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, `createdump` is not included (it's a CoreCLR tool). \n\nThe good news is that macOS handles crash reporting automatically, so I can point the user to where those reports are stored and how to access them.","outputTokens":405,"requestId":"F883:A64D3:6855F0B:725516F:69F9FFE4"},"id":"f38c0bcf-3af4-4d4b-b0c9-63caf09fc955","timestamp":"2026-05-05T14:34:23.084Z","parentId":"24bd1445-af68-4f17-a458-96a4e04a3e08"}
